op\n|Tullich Preceptory\n|\n|'''Knights Templar'''<br />given as a residence of Templars,<ref group=\"note\" name=\"TullichPreceptory\">Tullich Preceptory&nbsp;\u2014 J. Spottiswoode, ''An account of all the Religious Houses that were in Scotland at the time of the Reformation'' (included in R. Keith, ''An Historical Catalogue of the Scottish Bishops'' (Edinburgh, 1824)), p.435</ref> actually a parochial church held by the Templars and later the Hospitallers<ref group=\"note\" name=\"TullichPreceptory1\">Tullich Preceptory&nbsp;\u2014 ''Templaria: Papers relative to the history, privileges and possessions of the Scottish Knights Templars, and their successors the Knights of St. John of Jerusalem'' (1828), pp.5,7; ''Abstracts of charters and other papers recorded in the chartulary of Torphichen from 1581 to 1596'' (Edinburgh, 1830), p.9</ref>\n|\n|\n|- valign=top\n|Turriff Monastery\n|\n|'''Celtic monks'''<br />''founded'' before 1131;<br/>''dissolved'' after ''c.''1150\n|''St Congan's Church''\n|<ref>[http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/19164/details/turriff+celtic+monastery/ Site Record for Turriff, 'Celtic Monastery' Details]</ref>{{coord|57.5377583|-2.465567|format=dms|region:GB_type:landmark_source:enwiki|name=Turriff Monastery}}\n|}\n{{go to top}}\n\n===Angus===\n\n{|width=99% class=\"wikitable\"\n!width = 15%|Foundation\n!width = 5%|Image\n!width = 30%|Communities & provenance\n!width = 20%|Formal name or dedication <br />& ''alternative names''\n!width = 10%|Online references & location\n|- valign=top\n|[[Arbroath Abbey]]\n|[[File:Arbroath Abbey - geograph.org.uk - 3180.jpg|150px]]\n|'''Tironensian monks'''&nbsp;\u2014 from Kelso<br />''founded'' 1176 (1178) by [[William the Lion]];<br />church dedicated 8 May 1233;<br />church damaged by lightning 1380, monks removed temporarily to other locations during repairs;<br />mitred abbey 26 June 1396;<br />dissolved 1606\n|The Abbey Church of [[Thomas Becket|Saint Thomas of Canterbury]], [[Arbroath Abbey|Arbroath]