iable charters cited by Manuscript collections of Father Marianus Brockie (Scottish Catholic Archives, Edinburgh), pp.1254, 1255-7</ref>); ''reliable evidence of foundation lacking''\n|\n|\n|- valign=top\n|''Crail Priory''\n|\n|'''''nuns''' of unspecified order \u2013 apocryphal establishment''\n|\n|\n|- valign=top\n|[[Culross Abbey]] <sup>+</sup>\n|[[File:CulrossAbbey Aug2009 1.JPG|150px]]\n|'''Cistercian monks'''&nbsp;\u2014 from [[Kinloss Abbey|Kinloss]]<br />''dependent on'' Kinloss;<br />''founded'' before 1217/8;<br />''dissolved'' 1560;<br />erected into a temporal lordship for James Colville of Easter Wemyss (charters 1589, 1609);<br />currently partly in use as a parish church; ([[Historic Scotland|HS]])\n|The Abbey Church of [[St Mary|Saint Mary]], [[St Andrew|Saint Andrew]] and [[Saint Serf]], [[Culross Abbey|Culross]]\n|<ref>[http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/48040/details/culross+culross+abbey/ Site Record for Culross, Culross Abbey Details]</ref> {{coord|56.0583587|-3.6253274|format=dms|region:GB_type:landmark_source:enwiki|name=Culross Abbey}}\n|- valign=top\n|Cupar Blackfriars\n|\n|'''Dominican Friars'''<br />''founded'' 1348: petition by Duncan, Earl of Fife to the Pope 1348, to found a Dominican convent at his castle; permission ''granted'' by the Pope for the vicar-general in Scotland of the English provincial to build a church and oratory;<br />reportedly in a state of collapse by 13 November 1517;<br />proposal to close the house approved 1518, confirmed by Crown charter 4 October 1519; incorporated with the house at St Andrews, where the friars ''transferred'' 1519; ''granted'' to the Burgh of Cupar by [[James VI of Scotland|James VI]] 14 June 1572\n|St Katherine\n|<ref>[http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/31494/details/cupar/ Site Record for Cupar Details]</ref> {{coord|56.3197129|-3.0101375|format=dms|region:GB_type:landmark_source:enwiki|name=Cupar Blackfriars}}\n|- valign=top\n|''Cupar Red Friars''\n|colspan=4|purported '''''Trinitarian